// The `prelude.http` sub-module: a built-in HTTP client. `fetch` is an `external` whose calls route to the
// runtime's `http` reactor (an in-runtime `fetch`, not an FFI sidecar) via the `from "http"` clause. It is
// called as `http.fetch`.
//
// Because it is an external call it performs io: the call is impure (it carries the un-dischargeable `io`
// effect, which propagates to the run root), so it takes the strict, non-lifting call path. That gives the
// information-flow rules for free. The uniform rule: a private value may leave the runtime ONLY toward the
// request's destination server, through its deliberate submission surfaces — the header *values* AND the
// `body` are `string of private`, so a secret may be submitted as an auth header or inside a form body
// (Google's OAuth token endpoint wants the `refresh_token` in a POST body, with no header alternative). Both
// surfaces are revealed at a single transport boundary, where the request leaves for the one server the
// program named. `url` and `method` stay public `string`: a private value there is a type error, because a
// URL leaks into logs, caches, proxies, and `Referer` headers — places that are not the destination server.
// The response is public (declassified — it is the server's reply, not a function of the secret).
//
// Errors: a non-2xx response is returned as its `status` to branch on (`match (response.status) { ... }`).
// A request that never completes (DNS failure, refused connection, timeout, or a mid-flight restart) throws
// `fetch_error`, which bubbles from the call site to the nearest handler — so a caller can `use handler {
// request throw(error: http.fetch_error) -> never { break ... } }` to handle the failure locally and
// control retry.

@"An HTTP request never completed: DNS failure, refused connection, timeout, or a mid-flight runtime
restart. Thrown by `fetch`. (A response that did arrive is never an error — branch on its `status`.)"
data fetch_error(message: string)

@"Perform an HTTP request to @url@ with @method@ (e.g. \"GET\" / \"POST\"), the given @headers@ and @body@.
Each header value AND the @body@ may be a secret (an auth token, or a form-encoded `refresh_token`): both
are submitted to @url@'s server, while @url@ and @method@ stay public. Returns the response @status@ code,
its @headers@ (names lowercased; repeated headers joined with \", \") and its @body@ text. A request that
never completes throws `fetch_error` (catchable with `use handler { request throw(error: http.fetch_error)
-> never { ... } }`)."
external agent fetch(
  url: string,
  method: string,
  headers: record[string of private],
  body: string of private,
) -> { status: integer, headers: record[string], body: string } with prelude.throw[fetch_error] from "http"

@"A JSON API responded with a non-2xx status. Thrown by `post_json` (the raw `fetch` never treats an
arrived response as an error — this wrapper takes the opinionated JSON-API stance)."
data status_error(status: integer, body: string)

@"POST @body@ to @url@ as application/json with the given @headers@. The @body@ AND each header value may
be a secret (an auth token — an \"Authorization\" of \"Bearer <key>\" for OpenAI, an \"x-goog-api-key\"
for Gemini, built with `record.set(target = record.empty(), key = ..., value = ...)` — or a
`refresh_token` carried in the body of an OAuth token exchange): both are submitted only to @url@'s
server, which stays public. A @Content-Type: application/json@ default is merged beneath the caller's
headers — on a shared name the caller's value wins. Returns the response body text; a non-2xx status
throws `status_error`, a transport failure `fetch_error`. The canonical one-call shape of a JSON API
integration — build the body as `json` in Katari, post it, parse the reply as `json` in Katari."
agent post_json(
  url: string,
  body: string of private,
  headers: record[string of private],
) -> string with io | prelude.throw[status_error | fetch_error] {
  // The caller's headers merge as `record.merge`'s right side, so on a shared name (a caller that
  // sets its own Content-Type) the caller's value overrides the default.
  let effective_headers = record.merge(
    left = record.set(target = record.empty(), key = "Content-Type", value = "application/json"),
    right = headers,
  )
  let response = fetch(url = url, method = "POST", headers = effective_headers, body = body)
  if (response.status >= 200 && response.status < 300) {
    response.body
  } else {
    prelude.throw(error = status_error(status = response.status, body = response.body))
  }
}
